FIVE FROM JUNIOR CLASS
PLACED ON HONOR COURT

Five new members have been
elected to the Honor Court from the
Junior class. One person w'as se-
lected by each college. Those
chosen are Norwood Thornton,
Agriculture; Parks Shipley, Arts
and Sciences; M. B. Stevens, Edu-
cation; W. 11. Elgin, Engineering,
Ruth Mcßae, Home Economics.
Senior representatives of the
various colleges are last years’
Junior members. The old court
judges are E. K. Ensor, Agricul-
ture; Gilbert Dent, Arts and
Sciences; Phyllis Morgan, Educa-
tion; M. H. White, Engineering, and
Mary Riley, Home Economics.
The court will be called together
within a few days at which time
organization will be completed.
U. of M. 
Dr. A. F. Woods addressed mem-
bers of the Maryland Farm Bureau
on two occasions at the annual
meetings which w'ere held in Balti-
more during the past week. Many
other members of the University
faculty attended the lectures.
